      "category": "syntax",
      "language": "python",
      "level": 1,
      "difficulty": 1,
      "tags": ["control_flow", "conditionals"],
      "front": {
        "question": "What is the syntax for an if-elif-else statement in Python?",
        "hints": [
          "Python uses indentation instead of braces",
          "Don't forget the colons"
        ]
      },
      "back": {
        "answer": "if condition:\n    # code\nelif condition:\n    # code\nelse:\n    # code",
        "code": "x = 10\nif x > 15:\n    print(\"Greater than 15\")\nelif x > 5:\n    print(\"Greater than 5\")\nelse:\n    print(\"5 or less\")",
        "explanation": "Python uses indentation (4 spaces recommended) to define code blocks. Each condition ends with a colon. elif (else-if) and else are optional.",
        "related_concepts": ["indentation", "boolean expressions", "comparison operators"],
        "common_mistakes": [
          "Forgetting the colon after conditions",
          "Incorrect indentation",
          "Using = instead of == for comparison"
        ],
        "references": [
          "https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/controlflow.html"
        ]
      },
